          "body": "Verses 7-11 enumerate the tabernacle furnishings that Bezalel and the craftsmen are to make — tent of meeting, ark, mercy seat, table, lampstand, altar of incense, altar of burnt offering, laver, priestly garments, anointing oil, and fragrant incense. The list is exhaustive and the closing verdict is unambiguous: 'according to all that I have commanded you' (31:11). Creative Spirit-gifting does not license artistic improvisation when God has specified the design. The artisans are not innovators; they are executors of a divine blueprint revealed in chapters 25-30. This has permanent interpretive importance: wherever Scripture specifies the form and content of worship, the Spirit's equipping serves that specification rather than departing from it. The principle of exact correspondence between the heavenly pattern and the earthly construction (25:9, 40) makes the artisan's task one of faithful reproduction, not free expression. Swindoll notes that Bezalel's name means 'in the shadow of God' — the craftsman works under cover of the divine design, not in the open air of human creativity."
