          "body": "The Sabbath command in verses 14-15 carries a capital penalty clause not once but twice — 'shall surely be put to death' (vv. 14, 15). The doubled noun *shabbat shabbaton* ('a sabbath of complete rest,' v. 15) intensifies the totality of the required cessation. Profaning it means being 'cut off from among his people' (v. 14) — excommunication from the covenant community. The severity is proportional to the significance of the sign: to work on the Sabbath is not merely to violate a schedule but to repudiate the covenantal identity it marks. It is a public statement that Israel does not belong to the LORD who sanctifies, that the sign means nothing. Rabbinic tradition, reading this passage in conjunction with the tabernacle instructions it follows, derived the thirty-nine principal categories of labor forbidden on the Sabbath from the categories of work required to construct the tabernacle — precisely because Scripture places the Sabbath command *after* the tabernacle commission. Even the holiest work is not above the holiest rest. The principle is arresting: no goal, however God-ordained, suspends the God-given rhythm of work and cessation."
